Environment-climate: for a European New Deal
BRUSSELS – In Brussels as in European capitals, the "Green New Deal" is on all tongues, echoing the visionary economic program launched by President Franklin D. Roosevelt in 1933.
But this time, it's about the environment and the climate.
And Europe is the continent where we can and must act.
The European Union's commitment on these issues is not new: we have a common program since 1972.
Later in 2005, the EU established the first emissions rights exchange system, which remains the world's first CO2 market.
And in 2015, the EU played a driving role in the Paris Agreement negotiations, committing to reduce its own greenhouse gas emissions by 40% (basis: 1990 levels).
However, despite their importance, these measures are not enough to meet the challenges facing the world today.
Rising temperatures could lead to the complete disappearance of Arctic ice by 2050.
Bees and many other insects are dying off, while microplastic pollution is ubiquitous in our environment.
The victims of respiratory diseases are increasing in number as air pollution worsens.
We still have reasons to remain optimistic, however.
Let's look at these people, who day by day are ready to take action to question their way of life. Like these students and entire families descending into the streets of Stockholm, Prague, Brussels, and Milan every Thursday!
Businesses are also taking action, seeing the unparalleled economic potential of a green economy.
But it is the policies and politicians, at the national and European level, who too often lack ambition.
We have a window of opportunity to act. Let's seize it!
And let's make a green Europe our top political priority for the years to come, based on three key areas.
Firstly, Europe must become a carbon-neutral economy by 2050.
If we want to limit the warming of the planet to 1.5°C, we have no other choice: the EU's net emissions of carbon dioxide must be zero by the middle of the century.
Together, we can invest massively in the future of our mobility, energy-efficient buildings, and renewable energies, as well as in key technologies such as hydrogen batteries, new generations of solar panels, and green chemistry.
We also need to apply strict CO2 emission limits to new private cars, public transport, and maritime and air commercial transport.
And, by working closely with our automotive industry, we can make Europe the first continent for electric vehicles by 2030.
Secondly, Europe must play a leading role in responsible resource use and become a genuine circular economy that is waste-efficient.
Every year, 8 billion tonnes of materials are converted into energy or products in the European Union.
But only 0.6 billion tonnes come from recycling.
We need to do much better, which will require us to concentrate on four aspects: food waste and bioeconomy, textiles, construction, and rapidly evolving consumer goods.
Let's get to work today, for example, by launching an European initiative to fight against the programmed obsolescence of household appliances and electronic devices, and by abolishing plastics from our value chains.
Thirdly, we need to do much more to protect biodiversity.
According to WWF, wild species populations have decreased by approximately 60% worldwide since 1970.
The United Nations Conference on Biodiversity, which will be held in Beijing next year, will be decisive.
Once again, the EU must set the way.
We must strengthen EU legislation on species protection and put an ambitious plan on the table for the blue economy and the preservation of our seas.
We must also launch a genuine debate with our farmers (not against them!) on revising our standards and modernizing the common agricultural policy to accompany this green transition.
But these colossal tasks awaiting us, we will not be able to accomplish them if it's still the same – and the most vulnerable – who are asked to bear the costs.
All the measures considered must therefore be designed above all to minimize social costs.
And in parallel, we must work with our partners from today on for international cooperation, fighting against unfair competition.
Because it serves no purpose to have strict European rules on pesticides or forestry management if our imported food and timber are produced without respecting sustainability criteria.
These three projects could become the pillars of a Sustainability Pact at the heart of the EU's new political cycle.
Because we are in a sharp ecological debt situation, and it would be more than justified that the stability and growth pact, which applies to the public finances of member states, finds an equivalent for the objectives of a green Europe!
To achieve its objectives, this Sustainability Pact will require concerted action in all areas: climate, trade, taxation, agriculture, and innovation.
The EU should not be afraid to use its regulatory powers, for example: broadening the scope of legislation in the field of ecodesign and "extended producer responsibility" for products put on the market, could significantly stimulate innovation in favor of the environment.
Massive investments will also be necessary.
The European Commission estimates that the EU will need an additional 180 billion euros in investments each year to meet the commitments made under the Paris Agreement.
This is an achievable goal.
The European Investment Bank is already the largest multilateral provider of climate-focused funds.
The new EU budget and investment plan, leveraging private sector investments, could further strengthen the Union's action capacity.
The financial sector must play a fundamental role: thanks to the disclosure of climate-related financial information, we can encourage the world's largest financial institutions, such as the Norwegian sovereign fund and BlackRock, to adopt a long-term vision and avoid what Bank of England Governor Mark Carney called the "tragedy of the horizon".
Finally, although some member states will see this as a risky project, we must hold a debate on taxation, but also on subsidies for fossil fuels. In short, on the integration of sustainability into public spending.
Behind these tasks, these projects, the key lies in the method. For this "Green New Deal" to bear fruit, we must set ambitious objectives and "missions" with short and long-term impact that have real social resonance.
With member states and the European Parliament, we will need to determine a common roadmap and engage in in-depth discussions, just as we will with our regions, cities, businesses, trade unions, and civil society.
This can't be done overnight.
But we can't close our eyes and hold our breath to escape the reality of our environment anymore.
It's already very late to launch a "European Green New Deal". But it's not too late.
Let's not miss this new opportunity!
